snippet.textDisplay: Robert Downey Jr. was an amazing actor and performer, waaaay before Marvel...he went through a lot, as a young man, a prospect...a potential star...only he or his friends can truthfully share those years...but, just look at the "Chaplin", and you will realize that Robert's limitations were only his own. As an actor/performer potential...the guy is unparalleled...perhaps only comparable to Williams, Buster Douglas or Charlie himself...yes, that was my statement! Of course, there were/are amazing actors/performers before and after him, but if you really look at Robert's life/career, (well, this is a novel already, I hope the interested individual can do the research themselves), he is special.  RBJ is a rare example of an amazing artist to make it in a world dominated by money/influence and power (back to money:), all on his sheer talent (and a semi-decent agent)...completely underutilized (classically speaking, I suppose), but smartly folded into a modern interpretation (perhaps just modern), of art. The young Robert Downey Jr. could have played ANYTHING better or just as good as ANYONE in the first two thousand years or so... or just A.D. (this is being conservative) if given a chance or if being inspired to do so. Absolutely brilliant bloke...and as good as these Marvel movies ended up being (from a pure populous/XX century-information-overload-comic- theater-"reality", perspective)...he was/could have been soooo much better still!(but not recognized or accepted, of course). Thank you, Sir. Robert:)...And now...my apologies...the world was always dominated by power/money/armies=influence, those are the things that made the art world go 'round for sometimes now...or...forever/...whatever ...soooo..FB/twitter/Instagram ...kind of a thing...the words that describe the... World... did change, but the world as we know it, is just clicking away as always. We just like to think that we have changed, and got better...and we did...yet here we are...Joe is a great example of how far can a mix of, moderate skill/experience/cave proposition/modern interpretation/rough (staged...oh, yeah) appearance/ combined with money (yep, back at it) ...mixed with technology and ...friendly editing/ ha!...is shaping the experience and thoughts of young (and not so young) people /modern generations, craving for "thought", "truth"...and ultimately  entertainment that will become HISTORY, can become a new standard and perceived value. Cool...and perhaps more transparent that the Bible/Quran or whatever other "Holy Books" are out there (definitely more relatable)..UGH...I know, too many thoughts and too many words torite….Bed time...Go Robert...and Go Joe...perception is reality! ZZZZZZZ....

snippet.textDisplay:
The character Tony Stark was inspired by Howard Hughes. Surprised he didn't know that.
"Lee based this playboy's looks and personality on Howard Hughes,[9] explaining, "Howard Hughes was one of the most colorful men of our time. He was an inventor, an adventurer, a multi-billionaire, a ladies' man and finally a nutcase."[10] "Without being crazy, he was Howard Hughes," Lee said." https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron_Man

brown face isn't essentially offensive Ben Kingsley did the role of Gandhi in the 1982 biographical movie Gandhi no one to this day finds that offensive.
let's say a director is searching for an actor to play Martin Luther King and the best out of the auditions is a white guy well, why shouldn't he get the role? because he's white?! as long as the role is played with respect then I don't care if the guy is black white yellow green red or purple! it is a human being playing another human being and if it needs some darkening of the skin to make the character more believable then why not! it won't be a vaudeville minstrel show act but true history!
the same goes for a guy coming up first in an audition for a JFK movie and he's black who cares what color the actor is just a dab of makeup or CGI if its the best guy for the role let him do it despite the color of skin.
Darth Vader was secretly black until his mask was lifted!

snippet.textDisplay:
TBH, as the carer of a disabled brother, I really appreciated the "Simple Jack" character.

The "never go full retard" exchange is a biting piece of satire about how shallow Hollywood is about people with special needs, and more broadly about prejudice.

It's one of my all time favourite modern films, and I think Robert is spot on about Ben's overall talents.
